<Article
  title="What FORTIFIED Roof, Silver, and Gold Actually Require"
  description="Plain-English breakdown of IBHS FORTIFIED tiers — what Roof, Silver, and Gold each require, the evaluator process, and how projects fail certification."
  pillar="fortifying-vs-selling"
  lastUpdated="June 2026"
>

<p class="page-summary">This page explains what each IBHS FORTIFIED tier — Roof, Silver, and Gold — physically requires of your house, how the certification process actually works, and the paperwork mistakes that cost homeowners their designation even after the construction was done right. For whether the investment pays back in your state, see <a href="/fortifying-vs-selling/when-fortifying-pays-back/">when fortifying pays back</a>; this page covers what you're buying.</p>

<section class="fast-answer">
  <h2>The Fast Answer</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The three tiers follow how houses fail in wind.</strong> Roofs fail first, so FORTIFIED Roof hardens the roof system. Roof structures lift off walls next, so Silver ties the roof to the frame and braces the weak points. Wind enters through broken openings last, so Gold protects windows, doors, and the garage door.</li>
    <li><strong>Each tier includes everything below it.</strong> You cannot get Silver without meeting every Roof requirement, or Gold without meeting Silver.</li>
    <li><strong>Certification is a documentation process, not just a construction project.</strong> An independent, IBHS-certified FORTIFIED evaluator must document the work — including details that get covered up mid-construction. Hire the evaluator <em>before</em> the work starts, not after.</li>
    <li><strong>The designation expires.</strong> A FORTIFIED designation certificate is valid for five years; keeping it requires a redesignation inspection.</li>
    <li><strong>The standard was just updated.</strong> Projects permitted on or after November 1, 2025 must meet the 2025 FORTIFIED Home Standard, which tightened nailing requirements, added testing standards for roof vents, and now requires installation by a certified FORTIFIED roofing contractor.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>The Logic Behind the Tiers: How Houses Come Apart</h2>

  <p>FORTIFIED is a program of the Insurance Institute for Business &amp; Home Safety (IBHS), the insurance industry's research lab, which studies building failures by subjecting full-size test homes to hurricane-force wind. The program is voluntary and insurer-funded — read its claims with that in mind — but the engineering behind the tier structure is straightforward and matches what independent post-storm damage surveys find.</p>

  <p>Houses in windstorms tend to fail in a sequence:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>The roof cover goes first.</strong> Shingles peel, then wind-driven rain pours through the exposed deck seams into the attic and down the walls. Most of the dollar damage in a moderate hurricane is water through a compromised roof, not structural collapse.</li>
    <li><strong>The roof structure lifts.</strong> In stronger winds, suction loads pull the roof framing off the walls — especially at gable ends and over attached structures like porches and carports that were never tied in properly.</li>
    <li><strong>An opening breaks, and the house inflates.</strong> A failed window, door, or garage door lets wind pressurize the interior. Internal pressure pushing up while suction pulls from outside is how houses lose entire roofs and walls.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Each FORTIFIED tier blocks the next link in that chain. That is the whole program in one sentence: Roof stops the water, Silver stops the lift-off, Gold stops the pressurization. The program counted more than 100,000 designated homes nationwide as of May 2026 — with over 20,000 added in 2025 alone, across 34 states — so the standard your contractor quotes is no longer an exotic request.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>FORTIFIED Roof: The Foundation Tier</h2>

  <p>FORTIFIED Roof is where nearly everyone starts, and where most homeowners stop. Its core requirements as of the 2025 standard:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>A sealed roof deck.</strong> The single most important item in the entire program. A <strong>sealed roof deck</strong> (the plywood or OSB under your shingles, with every seam taped or covered by an adhered waterproof membrane so the deck itself sheds water) keeps rain out even if the storm strips the shingles. IBHS testing shows an unsealed deck can let in enough water to soak insulation, ceilings, and drywall — the difference between repairing a roof and gutting a house.</li>
    <li><strong>Ring-shank nails in an enhanced pattern.</strong> Ring-shank nails (nails with ridged shafts that grip the wood instead of pulling out under suction) fasten the deck to the framing on a tighter spacing than code requires. The 2025 standard made the tighter nailing pattern mandatory on all FORTIFIED roof decks.</li>
    <li><strong>Locked-down edges.</strong> Wider drip edge metal, fully adhered starter strips, and enhanced attachment at the roof perimeter — because shingle failure almost always starts at the edge.</li>
    <li><strong>Tested, rated vents.</strong> Under the 2025 standard, all roof-mounted vents must pass testing showing they keep wind-driven rain out. Ordinary turbine and box vents are a documented water-entry path in hurricanes.</li>
    <li><strong>A certified installer.</strong> The 2025 standard requires the roof be installed by a certified FORTIFIED roofing contractor — previously a recommendation, now a requirement for projects permitted on or after November 1, 2025.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The practical takeaway: a FORTIFIED Roof is a normal re-roof done with better fasteners, sealed seams, and disciplined edge details. If your roof is due for replacement anyway, the incremental cost over a standard re-roof is modest — the payback article walks through that math with examples.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>FORTIFIED Silver: Tying the Roof Down</h2>

  <p>Silver adds everything FORTIFIED Roof requires, plus the structural connections that keep the hardened roof attached to the house:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Roof-to-wall connections.</strong> Hurricane straps or clips (metal connectors nailed to both the roof framing and the wall framing) at the points where the roof structure bears on the walls. On an existing home, installing them usually means working from inside the attic or temporarily opening soffits.</li>
    <li><strong>Gable end bracing.</strong> A gable end (the triangular wall section under a peaked roof's end) acts like a sail in high wind and is a classic failure point. Silver requires gable ends over a certain height to be braced back into the structure.</li>
    <li><strong>Attached structures anchored.</strong> Porches, carports, and similar attached structures must be anchored to resist uplift — an under-built carport that peels away takes part of the main roof with it.</li>
    <li><strong>Chimneys and soffits secured.</strong> Chimney attachment and soffit installation are checked, since failed soffits are another wind-driven-rain entry path into the attic.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Silver is the awkward middle tier for retrofits: the work is invasive relative to its visibility (attic labor, soffit removal), and in some states the incremental insurance discount over Roof level is small. Where Silver clearly earns its cost is older coastal housing stock built before modern connection requirements — homes from the 1970s and 1980s that may have little more than gravity and toenails holding the roof structure down.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>FORTIFIED Gold: The Whole Load Path</h2>

  <p>Gold adds the final layer: a continuous load path and protected openings.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Continuous load path.</strong> A <strong>continuous load path</strong> (an unbroken chain of structural connections running from the roof, through the walls, down to the foundation) means wind forces on the roof are carried all the way into the ground instead of finding a weak link. On new construction this is a framing and hardware specification; on an existing home, verifying and completing it can require opening walls — which is why Gold retrofits of older homes are rare and expensive.</li>
    <li><strong>Every opening protected.</strong> Impact-rated windows and exterior doors, or tested storm shutters over standard ones. This is the requirement most people associate with hurricane hardening, and it exists to stop the pressurization failure mode.</li>
    <li><strong>A pressure-rated garage door.</strong> The garage door is the largest, weakest opening on most houses and a leading cause of catastrophic failure: once it buckles inward, the house inflates. Gold requires a door rated for the design wind pressure at your site, or a tested bracing system.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Honest guidance the program's marketing won't volunteer: Gold is mostly a new-construction standard. If you are building on a coastal lot, specifying Gold during framing adds a manageable percentage to construction cost. Retrofitting an existing home to Gold means new windows, new doors, a new garage door, and possibly opened walls — frequently $30,000 and up on top of Silver. If that money is on the table, compare it against the sell-side numbers in <a href="/fortifying-vs-selling/how-non-renewal-hits-your-homes-resale-price/">how non-renewal hits your home's resale price</a> before committing either way.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Hurricane, High Wind, and the Hail Supplement</h2>

  <p>Each tier comes in variants matched to your hazard, and the variant appears on your designation certificate:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Variant</th>
        <th>Who it's for</th>
        <th>What changes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>FORTIFIED Home – Hurricane</strong></td>
        <td>Coastal states (Gulf, Atlantic)</td>
        <td>Full requirements as described above, including wind-driven-rain details and, at Gold, opening protection rated for hurricane debris impact</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>FORTIFIED Home – High Wind</strong></td>
        <td>Inland wind and tornado-fringe regions (much of Texas, Oklahoma, the Plains, inland Southeast)</td>
        <td>Same tier structure calibrated to non-hurricane wind; some hurricane-specific details relaxed</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Hail supplement</strong></td>
        <td>Hail corridors (north Texas, Colorado Front Range, Plains)</td>
        <td>Added to a designation; requires a roof cover rated "Good" or "Excellent" on the IBHS Impact-Resistant Shingle Performance Ratings — note that many shingles marketed as Class 4 impact-resistant score below that bar in IBHS's own testing</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The hail supplement matters in places like Dallas–Fort Worth and Colorado precisely because carriers there are non-renewing over roof condition and hail claims history. If hail drove your problem, ask prospective insurers whether they recognize the supplement <em>before</em> choosing shingles — and check the specific product against the IBHS shingle ratings rather than trusting the "Class 4" label on the wrapper.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>The Certification Path — Where Projects Actually Fail</h2>

  <p>The construction is half the program. The other half is documentation, and it has a strict sequence:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Hire a FORTIFIED evaluator first.</strong> A <strong>FORTIFIED evaluator</strong> (an independent professional certified by IBHS, paid by you, not employed by your roofer) must document conditions before, during, and after the work. Evaluator certification itself is renewed every three years, so confirm yours is current on the program's directory.</li>
    <li><strong>The evaluator photographs the hidden details mid-job.</strong> The sealed deck seams, the nailing pattern, the straps — all get covered by shingles and drywall. If the evaluator wasn't there to document them, IBHS has no evidence the work was done, and no designation issues. This is the single most common and most expensive mistake: homeowners who order a "FORTIFIED roof" from a contractor, get the physical work, and only then look for certification. Too late.</li>
    <li><strong>IBHS reviews the evidence package.</strong> The evaluator submits photos and documentation; IBHS reviews and, if the project complies, issues the designation certificate.</li>
    <li><strong>The certificate runs five years.</strong> Keeping the designation alive requires a redesignation inspection at each five-year mark. Budget for it — an expired designation can mean a lost insurance discount at exactly the renewal where you need it.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Other recurring failure points worth knowing before you sign a contract: a roofer who is not a certified FORTIFIED contractor (disqualifying for projects permitted on or after November 1, 2025), unrated vents reused from the old roof, and edge metal installed to ordinary code rather than the FORTIFIED detail. Every one of these is cheap to get right during the job and expensive to fix after.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Which Tier Should You Target?</h2>

  <p>Both directions, plainly. The U.S. Treasury Federal Insurance Office (FIO), January 2025 report — <em>Analyses of U.S. Homeowners Insurance Markets, 2018–2022: Climate-Related Risks and Other Factors</em> — documented that premiums in the highest climate-risk ZIP codes already averaged 82 percent more than in the lowest-risk ZIPs, and rising; hardening a home you intend to keep is one of the few levers that pushes the other way. The U.S. Senate Budget Committee, December 2024 staff report — <em>"Next to Fall: The Climate-Driven Insurance Crisis Is Here and Getting Worse"</em> — is equally clear that retrofits do not guarantee continued coverage: carriers non-renew over modeled regional exposure, not just your individual roof. A FORTIFIED designation strengthens your file; it does not bind any insurer to keep you.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Roof due for replacement, wind or hail state:</strong> FORTIFIED Roof is usually the right call — the incremental cost is small when bundled into a re-roof you're paying for anyway.</li>
    <li><strong>Pre-1990s coastal home, planning to stay 10+ years:</strong> price Silver while the roofing crew is already mobilized; the connection work is cheapest done alongside a re-roof.</li>
    <li><strong>New construction on a high-wind lot:</strong> specify Gold in the plans. It is dramatically cheaper at framing time than ever after.</li>
    <li><strong>Wildfire- or flood-driven non-renewal:</strong> stop. FORTIFIED is a wind standard and will not move your risk score or your insurability. Spend nothing here.</li>
    <li><strong>Selling within five years:</strong> run the numbers on both pages of this pillar before spending; a designation can help a coastal listing, but you are unlikely to recoup a Silver or Gold retrofit in premium savings on that timeline.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="next-steps">
  <h2>What to Do in the Next 30 Days</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Identify your hazard and the matching variant.</strong> Hurricane, High Wind, or High Wind plus the hail supplement. If your problem is wildfire or flood, FORTIFIED is the wrong tool — redirect your budget now.</li>
    <li><strong>Find a certified FORTIFIED evaluator and a certified contractor through the program's directories.</strong> Verify both certifications are current. Talk to the evaluator before any contract is signed — sequencing is everything.</li>
    <li><strong>Get two quotes on your re-roof: standard code and FORTIFIED Roof.</strong> The difference between them is the true cost of the designation. Quotes that bundle it invisibly make the payback math impossible.</li>
    <li><strong>Ask your insurer — in writing — what discount each tier and variant earns.</strong> Ask specifically whether the hail supplement is recognized if you're in a hail state. Answers vary by carrier even inside mandate states.</li>
    <li><strong>Calendar the five-year redesignation.</strong> Put it in your phone now, with the evaluator's contact attached. An expired designation quietly forfeits the discount you paid to earn.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

